HEADWORD: Flasket
<hw>Flask"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. W.
<ets>fflasged</ets> a vessel of straw or wickerwork, <ets>fflasg</ets>
flask, basket, and E. <ets>flask</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A long,
shallow basket, with two handles.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In which they gathered flowers to fill their
<qex>flasket</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small flask.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A vessel in which viands are served.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>flat-bottomed</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>flat-bottom</ent>⟦br⟧
